    <header class="article-hero">
      <div class="container article-hero__inner">
        <div class="article-meta">
          <a class="kicker" href="/research/">Research &amp; Insights</a>
          <span class="dot" aria-hidden="true">•</span>
          <span class="cat">{meta.category}</span>
        </div>

        <h1 class="article-title">{meta.title}</h1>
        <p class="article-dek">{meta.excerpt}</p>

        <div class="byline">
          <span class="author">{meta.author}</span>
          <span class="dot" aria-hidden="true">•</span>
          <span class="date">{meta.dateLabel}</span>
          <span class="dot" aria-hidden="true">•</span>
          <span class="time">{meta.readTime}</span>
        </div>

        <div class="hero-media" aria-hidden="true">
          <img src={meta.image} alt="" loading="eager" />
        </div>
      </div>
    </header>

    <section class="article-body">
      <div class="container article-grid">
        <article class="prose">
          <p>
            A 403(b) plan is an employer-sponsored retirement plan for certain employees of public schools, tax-exempt
            organizations, and churches. The employer can purchase annuity contracts for eligible employees, or establish
            custodial accounts invested in mutual funds or other investments. In the case of annuity contracts, a 403(b)
            plan is sometimes referred to as a tax-sheltered annuity (TSA).
          </p>

          <h2 id="how">How does a 403(b) plan work?</h2>
          <p>
            Depending on the plan, contributions may come from the employee, employer, or both. Many 403(b) plans resemble
            401(k) plans: you elect to defer a portion of pay into the plan as an elective deferral, either pre-tax or Roth
            (if permitted).
          </p>

          <h2 id="who">Who can participate?</h2>
          <p>
            If any employee is eligible to make elective deferrals, generally all employees must be allowed to do so
            (“universal availability”), though certain groups can be excluded (e.g., employees working under 20 hours/week).
          </p>

          <div class="callout">
            <p class="callout-title">Watch automatic enrollment</p>
            <p>
              If your plan auto-enrolls you (e.g., at 3%), confirm both the contribution rate and investment lineup match your
              goals and time horizon.
            </p>
          </div>

          <h2 id="limits">What are the contribution limits?</h2>
          <p>
            You can defer up to a yearly limit (varies by year), and some plans allow additional catch-up contributions
            (age 50+). A unique 403(b) rule may also allow a special service-based catch-up (subject to eligibility).
          </p>

          <h2 id="ira">Can I also contribute to an IRA?</h2>
          <p>
            Participation in a 403(b) generally does not prevent IRA contributions, though income limits may affect traditional
            IRA deductibility or Roth IRA eligibility.
          </p>

          <h2 id="tax">Income tax considerations</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Pre-tax:</strong> tax deferred now, taxable on distribution</li>
            <li><strong>Roth:</strong> taxed now, potentially tax-free later if qualified</li>
            <li><strong>Employer match:</strong> typically pre-tax (taxable later)</li>
          </ul>

          <h2 id="access">When can I access my money?</h2>
          <p>
            Many plans restrict elective deferrals until age 59½, disability, or separation from service. Some plans offer loans;
            hardship withdrawals may exist but should be a last resort.
          </p>

          <h2 id="termination">What happens when I terminate employment?</h2>
          <p>
            You may leave assets in the plan, roll to an IRA, transfer to another plan, or take a distribution. Vesting rules may
            apply to employer contributions.
          </p>

          <h2 id="more">What else do I need to know?</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>RMDs typically begin at the applicable RMD age (and rules can change over time).</li>
            <li>If multiple vendors are offered, in-service transfers may be possible depending on plan rules.</li>
            <li>403(b) assets are generally protected under federal law in bankruptcy.</li>
          </ul>

          <hr class="sep" />

          <div class="article-footer">
            <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/research/">← Back to Research</a>
            <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/contact/">Talk with us</a>
          </div>
        </article>

        <aside class="aside" aria-label="On this page">
          <div class="aside-card">
            <p class="aside-title">On this page</p>
            <nav class="toc" aria-label="Table of contents">
              <a href="#how">How it works</a>
              <a href="#who">Participation</a>
              <a href="#limits">Contribution limits</a>
              <a href="#ira">IRA alongside</a>
              <a href="#tax">Tax considerations</a>
              <a href="#access">Accessing money</a>
              <a href="#termination">Termination</a>
              <a href="#more">More notes</a>
            </nav>
          </div>

